  "text": "Spontaneous and MG-evoked subthreshold activity Slow, spontaneous V,, fluctuations resembled those recorded with conventional sharp microelectrodes . In 25 neurons exhibiting robust fluctuations, the V,,, varied over a 15-25 mV range at a rate of about 0.5-3 Hz (Fig. 1) . The fluctuations were dominated by the rhythmic recurrence of a long-lasting hyperpolarizing potential (duration of about 200-600 msec, measured from midway between the maximum and minimum V,, amplitude). This potential peaked at -72 f 1.6 mV; its long duration produced a peak near this value in the L',, versus time histogram of spontaneous fluctuations for individual neurons (Fig. le) . Note also that depolarized phases of slow V,,, oscillations contained rapid depolarizing and hyperpolarizing fluctuations ( Fig. 1 A, inset); these fluctuations contributed to a broader peak at depolarized levels in the V, versus time histogram ( Electrical stimulation of the MG thalamus elicited in auditory cortex a short-latency EPSP (n = 26) followed by a slower, l-IPSP (n = 25; Fig. 2A ). The EPSP had an onset latency of 4.2 * 0.2 msec, a latency to peak of 10 f 0.5 msec, and an amplitude varying from about 2 to 15 mV, depending on when it occurred during the spontaneous V, fluctuations (i.e., the EPSP was generally smaller during depolarized phases, and larger during hyperpolarized phases; Fig. 2B ). The I-IPSP had a latency to peak of 127 + 8.2 msec, a duration of about 150-250 msec, and an amplitude varying from about 0 to 20 mV, again depending on the phase of I',, fluctuations. In 10 of 26 cells, responses to MG stimulation suggested the presence of an additional potential at a latency of 18-20 msec ( Fig. 2A, inset) . Passage of steady depolarizing or hyperpolarizing current through the recording electrode indicated that this intermediate potential reversed polarity near rest (Fig. 3A) . In eight cells where the reversal potential lay within the range of spontaneous V,,, fluctuations, MG stimulation during spontaneous depolarizations and hyperpolarizations (Figs. 2B, 3B ) demonstrated reversal of this potential at -56 f 1.2 mV (Fig. 2B, middle panel) . This reversal potential is intermediate to those of the EPSP and I-IPSP, and clearly differentiates the three potentials. Thus, the intermediate potential likely represents a distinct synaptic potential, and is most likely a Cl--mediated IPSP (Kmjevic and Schwartz, 1967; [CITATION_1] Douglas and Martin, 199 1) . While V, fluctuations in vivo make direct comparisons to in vitro data difficult, the three synaptic potentials observed here closely resemble, in terms of latency, time course, and voltage dependence, the short-latency EPSP, rapid e-IPSP, and long-lasting I-IPSP elicited in the in vitro auditory cortex . For the remainder of this report, we will refer to the synaptic potentials in vivo and in vitro using the same designations.",
